svg:text.svg:tspan: Scientists are looking at ways to provide enough food for the growing human
population — this includes the use of GM (genetically modified) crops.
Bt stands for It is a type of bacterium which produces
a toxin (poison) that kills many of the insect larvae that are harmful to crops.
The gene for the Bt toxin can be inserted into crops, such as cotton and corn,
which then produce the toxin in their stems and leaves — making them
resistant to the insect pests. The toxin is specic to insect pests — it’s harmless
to humans, animals and other insects.
The world’s population is rising very quickly — and it’s not slowing down.
This means that global food production must increase too so that we all have
access to enough food that is safe for us to eat and has the right balance of
nutrition — this is known as ‘’ (see pages 296-297 for more).
One way to increase food security may be through the use of GM crops.
However, not everyone agrees that these are a good idea.

There are concerns that the long term effects of exposure to GM crops
on human health and the environment aren’t yet known.
On the plus side, GM crops can increase the amount of food that a
crop provides (its yield). For example, crops can be produced that
are resistant to pests or are able to grow better in drought conditions.
GM crops could also be engineered to contain additional nutrients.
This could help to combat certain deciency diseases. These are common in
developing countries where some people’s diets may be lacking in nutrients.
Vitamin A deciency is common in parts of Africa and SE Asia. A lack of
vitamin A can lead to blindness. ‘Golden rice’ is rice that’s been engineered
to produce a chemical that’s converted in the body into vitamin A.
